{"/service/ndnp/mnhi/batch_mnhi_falstaff_ver01/data/sn86010115/00542864977/1937121601/0493.xml":{"full_text":"FME EIGHT\nEmployment Law\nEffective in 1938\n(Continued from page 1)\nlief or charity.\n\u201cOf course, benefit checks cannot\nand will not be given unemployed\nworkers for indefinite periods. The\nrate and duration of benefits will\ndepend upon each worker\u2019s indi\nvidual earnings record, for it is up\non the earnings of workers that\nemployers are contributing into the\nfund. The maximum weekly bene\nfit rate will be sls. The minimum\nwill be approximately $6. The max\nimum duration of benefits will be\n16 weeks in any one year.\n\u201cThe Minnesota State Employ\nment Service, which is free to work\ner and employer alike will operate\non a state-wide basis beginning on\nJanuary 1, 1938. It will have as its\nprincipal function the registration\nof unemployed workers and the\nseeking of jobs for them. The ser\nvice, which has absorbed the Na\ntional Re-Employment Service, will\noperate in conjunction with the un\nemployment compensation division,\nboth being divisions of the State In\ndustrial Commission\n\u201cState employment service offi\ncers will be located in cities and\ntowns throughout the state where\nthey can best serve the largest num\nber of persons. The offices will\nhave a direct connection with the\nunemployment compensation di vis-)\nion in that representatives of the\ndivision will serve in them to ac\ncept claims for benefits. While the\nemployment service seeks work for\nthe unemployed worker, the unem\nployment compensation division will\ndetermine the amount of benefits to\nwhich he is entited. If an eligible\nunemployed workers is not return\ned to work within two weeks after\nregistering and filing his claim, he\nwill begin to receive benefit checks\nfor each additional week of unem\nployment, up to 16 weeks, to which\nhis previous earnings makes it pos\nsible.\n\u201cThe aim of the law is to allevi\nate suffering, prevent sudden\nbusiness let-downs by sustaining\nbuying power, maintain the morale\nof workers, and systematically seek\nwork for the unemployed. Work will\nbe sought for all willing workers,\nwhether or not they are entitled to\nbenefits.\u201d\nHalf of Hunters\nAre Successful\nAt least one deer was shot for\nevery two hunters who purchased\nbig game licenses this year, accord\ning to preliminary estimates made\nlast week by the State Division of\nGame and Fish.\nApproximately 55,000 deer hunt\ning licenses were sold this fall. Ear\nly game reports received indicate\nthat 65 per cent of the hunters re\nporting got their deer, but it is es\ntimated that this figure will drop\nto about 50 per cent by the time\ntabulations are completed.\nFor the regular deer season in\n1936, 70,000 big game licenses were\nsold, with an estimated 41,000 or 55\nper cent of the hunters successful.\nIt is estimated that approximate\nly 220,000 Minnesotans engaged in\nsome form of hunting this year.\nAbout 284,000 small and big game\nlicenses were sold in 1936. The drop\nthis year is largely accounted for\nby shortening the pheasant season\nto three half days because of a re\nported scarcity of the birds.\nFederal duck stamp sales showed\na big rise this year, with incom\nplete reports from post office au\nthorities indicating that a total of\n100,000 may be reached as compar\ned to a 1936 total of 73,000.\nSmall game licenses dropped from\n214,000 in 1936 to 165,000 in 1937.\nThe pheasant kill decreased from\nan estimated 1,324,000 in 1936 to\n400,000 in 1937, the latter figure be\ning a rough estimate only.\nSecond Special Legislative\nSession Appears Possible\nUpon a backward turn of the\neconomic wheel, capitol observers\nat St. Paul admit, rests the possi\nbility of a second special session of\nthe Minnesota legislature which\nprobably would be held in February.\nThe wheel had been driving for\nward up to a few weeks ago. Then\nthe now-famed \u201cbusiness recession\u201d\nrumbled in the east. In Minnesota\nthe wheel may now be standing\nstill, its direction as uncertain as\nthe future of the state\u2019s relief pro\ngram.\nFor relief is the motivating force\nbehind the special session gossip.\nAlready three counties \u2014Beltrami,\nCarlton and Aitkin\u2014have appealed\nfor further aid. Koochiching may\nsoon do likewise. They all seek\nmore direct relief money.\nWhen the last extra session drew\nthe relief law, it did so optimisitcal\nly. For the first fiscal year it ap\npropriated $5,850,000 direct relief.\nFor the second fiscal year, ending\nJune 30, 1939, it provided only $2,-\n750,000.\nFor the present fiscal year in ad\ndition the legislature mustered sl,-\n750,000 as state aid to subdivisions\nunable to sponsor WPA projects;\nfor the next fiscal year, nothing.\nAll through the relief bill is writ\nten anticipation of expanding pri\nvate industry that was expected to\nreduce relief rolls and to steadily\ndiminish the roster of aid-depend\nent individuals.\nBagley-Copley F-L Club Has\nInteresting Meeting Saturday\nWith a good attendance and an\ninteresting speaker the monthly\nmeeting of the Bagley-Copley Far\nmer-Labor club on Saturday even\ning was a very successful event and\nindications point to continued\ngrowth of membership and atten\ndance at these meetings.\nGlen Thompson, a member of the\n4th ward Farmer-Labor club of\nMinneapolis, was the speaker. His\ntalk gave his audience a better un\nderstanding of the economic order\nunder which we live and to see\nbetter the necessity for thought and\naction toward correcting the weak\nnesses, the miscarriages and the\noutright perversions of contempor\nary capitalist society.\nE. L. Prestemon, chairman, pre\nsided and members were called up\non for remarks. Following the\nbusiness meeting lunch was served.\nThe club's next meeting will be\nsome time in January, the date to\nbe announced later after a program\nhas been arranged.\nHerefords Being Held for Market O n Big Scale\nPublic Library\nGiven Donations\n(Continued from page 1)\nNew Books\nNorthwest Passage .Roberts\nHome for Christmas.. .Douglas\nStag Line Lorimers\nThe Country Kitchen Lutes\nReturn to Religion Link\nChildren\u2019s Books\n5 Books in the Happy Hour Ser\nvice.\nLonesomest Doll Broen\nWinnie the Poo Milne\nWater Babies Kingsley\nChildren of the Alps and Heidi\nSpyri\nEnglish Fairy Tales Jacobs\nSnip, Snap, Snurr and the But\ntered Bread\nAdventure of a Brownie. .Craik\nJohnny Cross\u2019 Garden... Brook\nStories from Arabian Nights\nFor Older Children, Jr. High, Etc.\nAn Old Fashioned Girl\nCall of the Wild; White Fang\nLondon\nGreyfriars Bobby Atkinson\nGay Neck Mukerji\nJust So Stories Kipling\nScouting with Kit Carson\nScouting with Daniel Boone\nBeloved Vagabond Loeke\nPrince and the Pauper\nCaptains Courageous... .Kipling\nJacqueline and the Carrier Pig\neons Seaman\nModern Handbook for Girls\nLavders\nCaptain Blood\nWind in the Willows.\nState WPA Quota for Month\nFilled; Total Now is 35,000\nWPA employment in Minnesota\nhas reached 35,000, the quota limit\nfor December, and no new assign\nments can be made until after Janu\nary 1, said a statement issued this\nweek by Victor Christgau, state ad\nministrator, after his return from\na regional conference in Chicago.\n\u201cIf more persons are to be em\nployed as a result of the current\nbusiness recession,\u201d he said, \u201cit will\ndepend on legislation effecting funds\navailable for WPA. We are now op\nerating under the 1937 Emergency\nRelief Act, passed last June. This\ncontemplated an employment load\nsmaller than had been carried in\n1936, and appropriated funds suffi\ncient to carry such a program to\nJuly 1,1938. Now we are being ask\ned to provide employment for a ma\nterially larger number of persons.\nObviously, we do not have the funds\nwith which to meet these new de\nmands\nThe legislation passed six months\nago and before the current increase\nin unemployment, prescribed that\nthere should be no deficiency appro\npriation; that no more than the\nmoney allocated should be spent. If\nadditional funds become available,\nWPA will be able to quickly expand\nits employment, as the Minnesota\nadministration has a reserve of pro\njects that can be put into immedi\nate operation.\nRailroad Fares Were\nIncreased December First\nThe Interstate Commerce Com\nmission recently authorized a pas\nsenger fare increase on western and\nsouthwestern railroads among\nwhich are included the Great Nor\nthern.\nAlthough the new fares went in\nto effect Dec. 1, the change was not\nnoticeable in short distance trans\nportation but was placed on sleep\ning car fares, 30-day round trip\ntickets, all-year excursion fares, six\nmonths round trip fares, and one\nway transcontinental fares.\nEd Widseth May Run for\nSheriff of Polk County\nEd Widseth has finished with the\nfootball wars as a member of the\nNew York Giants, winning second\nall-American honors in some polls.\nNow he considers turning to other\npolls. He may run for sheriff of\nPolk county, with headquarters at\nCrookston.\nHOUSEHOLD HINTS\nOilcloth is a satisfactory covering\nfor the bottom of cupboard draw\ners. It needs only to be wiped off\nwith a damp cloth to freshen it.\nA clothespin may be used for re\nmoving food which has adhered to\npans and is much easier to clean\nthan a brush or pad. Soap the dish\ncloth before dipping in cleanser\nwhen cleansing sooty bottoms of\nkitchen ware. The soot is easily re\nmoved and the dish cloth rinses\nclean.\nAN INSPIRATION\n\"A merry heart doeth good like\na medicine\n470 head of Herefords are be\ning fed for market on the Till\nman Thompson stock farm, east\nof Appleton. They are Rocky\nMountain cattle brought into the\nstate from Montana, They are be\ning fed silage, shelled corn, oil\nmeal and other roughages and\nconsume five tank wagon loads\ndaily.\nBagley High is Victor in\nMclntosh Game Last Friday\nBagley high school won its sec\nond basketball game of the season\nat Mclntosh last Friday evening by\nthe score of 33 to 19. The score\nwas tied at 11 all at the half, but\nin the last half of the contest Bag\nley surged forward.\nIn the Mclntosh game Lewie Op\nheim at forward proved to be high\npoint man, making eight field goals\nand three free throws for a total\nof 19 points. The entire Bagley\nteam showed up well. Alfon Lind\ngren accounted for nine points at\nforward, Cameron and Neujahr each\nhad one free throw, and Clarence\nMuckala played a steady, depend\nable game at guard and also ac\ncounted for three points. For Mc-\nIntosh W. Berg proved the star,\nand this player will bear watching\nby other opponents during the sea\nson.\nThe next game on the schedule\nfor Coach Harry E. Ahiin\u2019s players\nwill be this Friday evening, when\nGonvick plays on the Bagley floor.\nThis is also the final game until af\nter the holidays.\nIn the sub-district standings Er\nskine was at the top of the heap\nthe first of the week, with Bagley\nalso having at that time a 1000 per\ncent record. The Erskine team, un\nder Irwin Mickelson, former Bag\nley assistant coach, showed prom\nise last year of being one of the\nbest team in this territory.\nIn the games played Tuesday,\nDec. 7, Mentor beat Fertile by a\n19-17 score, and Erskine beat Foss\nton 25 to 10. On last Friday, Dec.\n10, Erskine beat Clearbrook 29-12,\nGonvick beat Fosston 27-12, and\nMentor beat Oklee 32 to 8.\nThe sub-district standings early in\nthe week were as follows:\nErskine 3 0 ^999\nBagley 1 0 1000\nGonvick 2 1 666\nMentor 2 1\nFosston 1 2 333\nMclntosh 1 2 333\nClearbrook 1 3 250\nOklee 0 3 000\nFosston did not provide as much\ncompetition as had been anticipated\nTuesday evening, and Bagley won\nthe game by a score of 18 to 9\nwithout the services of Lewis Op\nheim, forward. The Bagley team\ntook the lead early in the game,\nand at no time was in serious dang\ner. Bagley\u2019s playing was not with\nout fault, but the Fosston team did\nnot seem to click.\nThe individual Bagley players\nperformed quite well in the Tues\nday night game. Alfon Lindgren\nwas high point man with eight\npoints, and played a snappy game.\nIrvin Stenborg was next with four\npoints, and Captain Kenny Neujahr\nhad three points. Oscar Lukkasson\nmade a field goal and Clarence\nMuckala, who again played a neat\nand efficient gme at guard, made\none free throw. At the half Bag\nley was in the lead by a score of\n9 to 3, and Bagley maintained a\ngood lead easily.\nFast Plummer Quintet Downs\nBagley Independents 21 to 13\nPlummer, last year\u2019s champions\nin the independent tourney at Er\nskine, won from the Bagley inde\npendent basketball team here Fri\nday by a score of 21 to 13. At the\nhalf Plummer was only a couple of\npoints ahead of the Pirates, but\nlengthened the lead in the last part\nof the game.\nThe Pirates will play at Gonvick\nthis (Thursday) evening, and on\nFriday evening will go to Plummer\nfor a return game. They will con\ntinue their travels by going to Red\nLake Sunday for a contest with the\nIndians.\nThe box score for the game fol\nlows:\nfg ft pf\nL. Halseth, f 2 0 0\nR. Holt, f 0 0 2\nI. Lee, f 0 0 0\nP. Berg, f 0 0 0\nA. Anderson, c ........2 1 4\nE. Sletten, g 0 0 0\nP. Halseth, g 1 0 0\nC. Fox, g 0 0 0\nE. Lhotka, g 1 0 2\nFARMERS\u2019 IN\nTraveling Alone from Norway\nxs k 1\nf \u2022Xw.- \u25a0\u25a0'Hit\nfl <fl\n-\u2018'-\u2019a\nWith her name and destination\nstitched on her coat and sweater\nElinor Richard, 8-year-old orphan\nwaits at the Traveler\u2019s Aid Socie\nty before resuming her journey to\nSan Francisco, where her uncle\nOtto Wulff, waits to adopt her.\nElinor knows only two words\n^Mickey Mouse\u201d, the name of her\npet Mickey Mouse doll, in the\nEnglish, but explained to passen\ngers on the steamer Stavanger\nfjord enroute to New York that\nshe was an American returning\nhome. She was born in San Fran\ncisco, but her mother took her to\nChristiansand, Norway, when she\nwas five years old. While acquir\ning a voluable command of Nor\nwegian, she forgot the English\nshe knew.\nSANTA AND HIS PACK\nWith Christmas just around the\ncorner, toymakers announce that\nthe volume of business has been\ngreater this season than at any time\nfor the past seven years. They\nhave manufactured a quarter of a\nbillion dollars worth of toys for\nthis Christmas and distributed them\nto the trade, so it is evident Santa\u2019s\npack is going to be well filled this\nyear, especially for the children.\nIt should be of interest to learn\nin connection with this report that\nthe toymakers have this year steer\ned clear of war toys, which have\nbeen the rage in years gone by.\nThrough an agreement reached ear\nly last spring they reduced the\nmanufacture of toy cannons, guns,\nsoldiers and all other type of toys\nthat smack of war and instead have\nturned out more toys stressing sci\nentific, industrial and transporta\ntion lines. They consist of many\ningenious mechanical features, and\nthe airplane, the auto, the stream\nlined locomotive along with toys\nthat do marvelous acrobatic stunts\nwill this year direct the childish\nmind away from war and its des\ntruction.\nThis is good news, and it reflects\nthe sane judgment of the men who\ndesign and manufacture the things\nwhich go to make up Santa\u2019s pack.\nFor Sale\n1 1936 V 8 FORD TUDOR\nTOURING, with radio\nand heater.\n1 1935 V 8 TUDOR, Regu\nlar, overhauled.\n1 1935 V 8 FORD TRUCK.\n1 1933 V 8 TUDOR FORD,\nregular.\n1 1931 MODEL A FORD\nTRUCK, Dual wheels.\n1 CHEVROLET.\n1 DURANT.\n1 WHIPPET.\nNew DeLuxe and Standard\nModeb on Display\nFriday, Dec. 17\nNasset Motor Co.\nbagley,\nto San Francisco\nRural Credit Land\nSales Are Tripled\nSales of rural credit land totaled\napproximately 28,000 acres of land\nsold to 122 purchasers for a total\nof $822,000 in 1937, according to a\nreport of T. H. Arens, Conservator\nof Rural Credits. This is more\nthan three times the number of\nsales of 1936, nearly three times the\nnumber of acres, and a large in\ncrease in total receipts. The in\ncrease in receipts is not as large in\nproportion to the number of farms\nsold due to the fact that many of\nthe sales were in the northern part\nof the state this year where land\nis comparatively cheap. Over sev\nenty per cent of the sales are made\nin the northern counties.\nMr. Arens attributes the large in\ncrease in sales to better crops and\nprices, more attractive contracts to\nformer owners, and the lower inter\nest rate. The 1937 legislature estab\nlished 4 per cent, as the interest\nrate charged the buyers, and liber\nalized the crop payment contract.\nThe Department of Rural Credits\nhas received more rentals in ad\nvance than any year in its history\naccording to T. H. Arens, Conserva\ntor. The total rental receipts for\nNovember, 1937 are $127,222.62, in\nNovember, 1936, the rental receipts\nwere $69,703.07. The total rents col\nlected for the eleven months of 1937\nis $811,727.79 as compared with\n$611,655.90 the total of 1936. Mr.\nArens believes the total rentals for\n1937 may reach one million dollars.\nNot nearly as high percentage of\ntotal rentals in 1936 were paid in\ncash as for the nresent year.\nIn the opinion of Mr. Arens this\nis due to the better crops, and the\ngood prices paid for cattle in late\nsummer and early fall. The total\nreceipts of the department for crop\npayment rent will be considerably\nlarger this year because of the bet\nter crops.\n\u2022While sales have been made for\nthe most part within the state, the\nDepartment of Rural Credits has\nbeen receiving inquiries from every\npart of the country. Over sixty per\ncent of the inquiries have been\nfrom other states. South Dakota\nleads followed by North Dakota, lo\nwa, Illinois, Indiana and Wisconsin.\nA few of these are former owners.\nFSA Debt Adjustment Work\nIs Reviewed by Supervisor\nIn Minnesota nearly 1800 farmers\nmade settlement of their debts dur\ning the past two years, with the aid\nof Farm Debt Adjustment supervis\nors, county rehabilitation supervis\nors, and farm debt adjustment com\nmittees, according to a report re\nceived from the office of Lloyd I.\nNelson, state director of the Farm\nSecurity Administration, by Mr.\nWm. Anderson, rural rehabilitation\nsupervisor for Clearwater and Bel\ntrami counties.\nThe report indicates that since\nthe program began in the fall of\n1935, 1,746 cases were settled. Prior\nto adjustment the total indebted\nness of these farmers was $6,660,-\n397, or an average of $3,791 per\nfarm, and through the help of the\nvoluntary committees this indebted\nness was reduced 31.3 per cent, or\nabout $1,195 per farm.\n\u201cIn a large majority of the ad\njusted cases,\u201d Mr. Anderson said,\n\u201crefinancing was involved and this\nresulted in the payment of many\nold debts. The Farm Security Ad\nministration supplied loans for 915\nof the cases which were refinanced.\nThe Federal Land Bank, local banks\nand individuals provided the loans\nfor most of the remainder.\nIn commenting on the farm debt\nadjustment work, which together\nwith rural rehabilitation loans, form\nan important part of the Farm Se\ncurity Administration\u2019s activities,\nMr. Anderson added, \u201cthe FSA\u2019s\nrural rehabilitation division cannot\nbe considered entirely a credit ag\nency, because in addition to the\nloaning of funds the program in\nvolves improvement of farming\npractices, through farm manage\nment supervision and the keeping\nof farm and household accounts and\nbudgets.\n\u201cIn working out the farm plan,\non which rural rehabilitation loans\nare based, it is often found that the\nprospective borrower\u2019s indebtedness\nis too high to ever permit repay\nment,\u201d he continued. \u201cLocal volun\ntary Farm Debt Adjustment com\nmittees work with the creditors and\nfarm debtors to bring about a settle\nment suitable to all.\u201d\nThis debt adjustment service is\navailable not only to borrowers of\nthe rural rehabilitation division of\nthe FSA but to all farmers, Mr. An\nderson said. Farmers desiring aid\nmay contact the county rural re\nhabilitation supervisor or write di\nrectly to L. J. Paulson, State Farm\nDebt Adjustment Supervisor, Minne\nsota Building, St. Paul.\nIt is high time that American fath\ners and mothers turned the inter\nests of their children away from\nthoughts of war and directed their\nminds more toward the worth-while\nthings of life.\nIM\n4^^\nFive Face Death for Folsom Riot\nDeath sentence having been\npassed on five Folsom convicts\nwho rioted in September and\nkilled the Fosom warden and\nguard, this photograph shows\nthem being brought to San Quen-\nAsks Pension for War of 1812\nMiss Mary Ellen White, 82, mak\ning her home this winter with Mr.\nand Mrs. Ray Satchell, in Eldora,\nlowa, is believed to be one of two\nsurviving daughters o fa veterans of\nthe war of 1812. Her home is in\nOskaloose, lowa, where she was\nbom Oct. 14, 1855. Miss White and\nMrs. Satchell\u2019s mother were sisters.\nThe only other surviving daughter,\naccording to a press release is Mrs.\nEsther Ann Hill Morgan, of Inde\npendence, Oregon.\nCaribou May Roam Forests\nof State Again, Reports Cox\nCaribou once more may roam\nnorthern Minnesota forests, under\nplans of W. T. Cox, regional for\nester-biologist of the U. S. depart\nment of agriculture.\nOnce common, the animals for\nyears have had difficulty withstand\ning fires .poaching and wolves. To\nday the dwindling band, only one\nremaining in the United States,\ncontains but four animals. But ar-\nONDISPLAY\nFRIDAY\nNEW 1938\nDeLuxe Model\ni FORDSI\nNasset Motor Co.\nFURNITURE\nAUCTION SALE\nCarload of new and used Furniture\nconsigned to Martin Hanson will be sold at public auction\nW. O. W. HALL, GONVICK\nSATURDAY, DEC. 18\nSale Starts at 1:00 o\u2019clock p. m.\nSTOCK CONSISTS OF rocking chairs, dining room sets,\nsewing machines, buffets, mattresses, dufolds, beds, dress\ners, piano, tables, writing desks, library table, rug\u2014every\nthing in household goods.\nBUY NOW AND SAVE MONEY!\nA. DIAMOND, AUCTIONEER\nA number of new articles suitable for Christmas gifts\n^^rHissiiftViNG VALUE\nO TOPS THEM AU.\nSave money without sacrificing shav-\ning comfort! Probak Jr. Blades give you v\nknown quality at a record low price. f\nSpecially processed to remove stubborn\nbeards smoothly and cleanly, these fa\nmous double-edge blades are priced at 4\nfor only 10\u00a3 Buy a package today J\nio*\ntin prison, there to await execu\ntion in the newly adopted gas\nchamber method. Manacled to\ngether, left to right: Albert Kes\nsel, Wesley Eudy, Fred Barnes,\nRobert L Cannon, Ed Davis.\nrangements are being completed to\nobtain 10 additional head from\nCanada They will be shipped to\nBaudette, Minn., and taken out 40\nmiles to the enclosure being pre\npared for them. There they will\nfind their favorite food, some lone\nsome companions, and the protec\ntion needed to perpetuate the breed.\nTHE FAMILY DOCTOR\nGargling with peroxide is recom\nmended for sore throat. Or use\none-half teaspoon soda dissolved in\nhalf glass of warm water as a\ngargle. An aspirin table dissolved\nin water is an effective gargle, or\nuse salt in vinegar.\nRev. N. Demy says:\nI have found nothing in the\npast 20 years that can take the\nplace of Dr. Miles Anti-Pain\nPSU. They are a sure relief for\nmy headache.**\nSufferers from Headache,\nNeuralgia, Toothache, Backache,\nNeuritis, Muscular Pains, Peri\nodic Pains, write that they have\nused Dr. Miles Anti-Pain Pills\nwith better results than they had\neven hoped for.\nCountless American house\nwives would no more think\nof keeping house without Dr.\nMiles Anti-Pain Pills than with\nout flour or sugar. Keep a pack\nage in your medicine cabinet and\nsave yourself needless suffering.\nAt Drug Stores\u2014-25c and fLOO\nt K IM7","height":"26193","width":"19374"}}
